<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="403" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[745,1339,2748,3167]" pageId="10" pageNumber="403">
Evidence from mtDNA and nDNA sequences classifies 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Altobello" authorityYear="1926" box="[1001,1170,2858,2891]" class="Mammalia" family="Soricidae" genus="Sorex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="10" pageNumber="403" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="samniticus">S. samniticus</taxonomicName>
close to the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[749,886,2902,2931]" class="Mammalia" family="Soricidae" genus="Sorex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="10" pageNumber="403" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="araneus">S. araneus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Merriam" authorityYear="1900" box="[964,1131,2902,2931]" class="Mammalia" family="Soricidae" genus="Sorex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="10" pageNumber="403" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tundrensis">S. tundrensis</taxonomicName>
groups, being sister to both clades and is here included in the monotypic 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Altobello" authorityYear="1926" box="[999,1168,2976,3009]" class="Mammalia" family="Soricidae" genus="Sorex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="10" pageNumber="403" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="samniticus">S. samniticus</taxonomicName>
group. This is supported by their differing karyotype structure. Thus, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Altobello" authorityYear="1926" box="[994,1168,3063,3088]" class="Mammalia" family="Soricidae" genus="Sorex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="10" pageNumber="403" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="samniticus">S. samniticus</taxonomicName>
lacks a sex chromosome trivalent and has only one Y-chromosome. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[136,558,3174,3207]" pageId="10" pageNumber="403" type="distribution">
<caption box="[136,558,3174,3207]" inLine="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="403" targetBox="[133,724,2755,3169]" targetPageId="10">
<paragraph blockId="10.[136,1343,3174,3482]" box="[136,558,3174,3207]" pageId="10" pageNumber="403">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,312,3174,3207]" pageId="10" pageNumber="403">Distribution.</emphasis>
Endemic to Italy.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="403" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[136,1343,3174,3482]" pageId="10" pageNumber="403">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,385,3217,3246]" pageId="10" pageNumber="403">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 68-78 mm, tail 33-45 mm, hindfoot 11-13 mm; weight 6-5-10 g. The Apennine Shrew is large. Tail is short, usually no longer than 50% of head-body length. Pelage is unicolored. Back and belly are brownish chestnut, but belly is somewhat lighter. There is no distinct demarcation between back and belly colors. Chromosomal complement has 2n = 52 and FN = 52, with 25 pairs of acrocentric autosomes. X-chromosome and Y-chromosome are acrocentric. Up to two supernumerary B-microchromosomes are occasionally found in the karyotype.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="403" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="10.[1404,2611,294,729]" pageId="10" pageNumber="403">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1405,1517,294,327]" pageId="10" pageNumber="403">Habitat.</emphasis>
Stream valleys and bogs or along fences and roadbeds in low mountains up to elevations of 1160 m but not higher. The Apennine Shrew avoids arid habitats.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
